# {{non-gloss definition|A [[mild]] [[oath]] expressing [[surprise]], [[disbelief]] or [[annoyance]]. It is [[stereotype|stereotypically]] regarded as being [[utter#Verb|uttered]] by [[pirate]]s.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=James Roberts|title=Rule Britannia! A Loyal Sketch, in Two Acts, as Performed with Universal Applause at the [[w:Theatre Royal Haymarket|Theatre Royal, Haymarket]]|location=London|publisher=Printed for Hookham and Carpenter, Old and New [[w:Bond Street|Bond-street]]|year=1794|section=Act II, scene i|page=26|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=pNdZAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA26|oclc=228762542|passage=I was informed I ſhould meet my dear Anna ſomewhere in theſe woods: I have been ſteering all points of the compaſs, but in vain. However, after having given chaſe to an enemy, ſhall I tamely haul my wind when my miſtreſs is in view? No;—'''ſhiver my timbers''' if I do. The man who meanly deſerts his King or his miſtreſs, deſerves to be ſhot for a traitor to both!}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=[Edward Dubois]|authorlink=Edward Dubois|chapter=XII|title=A Piece of Family Biography. In Three Volumes|location=London|publisher=Printed for [[w:John Bell (publisher)|J[ohn] Bell]], no. 148, [[w:Oxford Street|Oxford-Street]], opposite [[w:Bond Street|New Bond-Street]]|year=1799|volume=II|page=216|pageurl=https://books.google.com.sg/books?id=v60BAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA216|oclc=753432205|passage=I weighed anchor inſtantly, and bore up right a-head to Dynevawr-houſe as faſt as my wooden leg would carry me. {{...}} '''Shiver my timbers'''! what do you think I found 'em at? Split my wind if there was not a gang, with Mrs. Martha at the head, working away at the temple which was built for us to take our grog in.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Robert Louis Stevenson|authorlink=Robert Louis Stevenson|chapter=At the Sign of the ‘Spy-Glass’|title={{w|Treasure Island}}|location=London; Paris; New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Cassell (publisher)|Cassell & Company, Limited]]|year=1881–1882|year_published=1883|page=66|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=3dwNAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA66|oclc=702939134|passage="The score!" he burst out. "Three goes o' rum! Why, '''shiver my timbers''', if I hadn't forgotten my score!" And, falling on a bench, he laughed until the tears ran down his cheeks.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Daisy Jordan|chapter=19|title=Wild about Harry|location=London|publisher={{w|Bantam Books}}|year=2005|page=263|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=sYDWwrrupJwC&pg=PA263|isbn=978-0-553-81726-3|passage=When I wake up the next morning there's a seagull on my windowsill. {{...}} They're such big birds, seagulls, so loud and cocksure and arrogant. If they could speak they would all sound like sailors. All ''avast!'' and ''ahoy there!'' and '''''shiver me timbers'''!'' and they'd smoke reedy pipes and down flagons of foamy ale.}}

